        <figure id="f0502A92" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic filename="../fign00/N0023946.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                     scalefitheight="392px"/>
            <caption>Figure 2. Dana Model S110 Wheel Differential Assembly, Disassembled View</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Pinion nut</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Pinion flange</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Drive pinion oil seal slinger</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Drive pinion oil seal</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Outer pinion bearing</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Outer pinion bearing cup</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Pinion preload spacer (selective)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Inner pinion bearing cup</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Inner pinion bearing</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Rear axle drive pinion</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Carrier housing</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Differential bearing caps</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Differential bearing cap bolts</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the pinion nut.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a93" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1961A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Hammering on the pinion flange will close in the bearing bores and misalign the flange lugs. This
                    will result in premature failure of the journal needle bearings. Serious damage will also occur
                    internally to the differential ring gear and pinion set or pinion bearings by hammering on external
                    components. Remove and install the pinion flange using only the procedures in this section.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Using the special tool, remove the pinion flange.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a94" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../fign00/N0020650.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the pinion seal.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a95" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1963A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Position a block of wood under the pinion to avoid damage to the gear teeth.</para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>The outer bearing is press fit.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press the pinion through the outer pinion bearing, and remove the pinion.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a96" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1964A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the pinion preload spacer.</para>
            <para>&#8226; Measure and record the spacer thickness. Set the spacer aside for use in assembly.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a97" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1965A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If reusing the gear set, remove the inner pinion bearing with a suitable puller.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a98" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1966A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If new pinion bearings are being installed, remove the outer and inner pinion bearing
                cups.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a99" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1967A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Alkaline cleaning solutions will damage machine surfaces. Use only emulsion cleaners or
                    petroleum-based cleaning solvent.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Use soft, clean, lintless towels to dry the components.</para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Never spin-dry bearings with compressed air. This will damage the mating surfaces due to a lack of
                    lubrication.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>After drying, lightly coat the components with rust inhibitor or clean lubricant to prevent damage
                    from corrosion. Wrap all components that are going to be in storage for a prolonged period in wax
                    paper.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Clean and dry the components as necessary.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect the pinion flange for grooves in the sealing surface caused by contamination.</para>
            <para>&#8226; If grooves are detectable with a fingernail, repair the flange with a CR-approved sleeve or
                install a new pinion flange.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a100" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1968A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
